Augmentation of a global navigation satellite system (GNSS)
Furkan Danishman, Nga Nguyen
Faculty of Science, York University
Introduction/Objective
In dense urban environments, ulizing Global Navigaon Satellite System (GNSS)
for localizaon presents numerous challenges due to:
Signal obstrucons caused by tall buildings and vehicles.
Mulpath interference from surrounding structures.
This study addresses these challenges, parcularly in context of data collected
from smartphones equipped with GNSS receivers.
Invesgang outlier detecon methods to enhance reliability of GNSS data
in urban sengs.
Highlighng dierences between each technique to give insight about
advantages and disadvantages.
Methodology
Our data consists of 132 satellites and 1631 epochs, collected by driving a vehicle
equipped with Xiaomi and Samsung smartphones around urban areas.
Outlier detecon methods were implemented to idenfy and migate localizaon
errors caused by non-line-of-sight and mulpath anomalies. The methodology of
this study goes beyond the limitaons of prior studies and has never been imple-
mented in context of GNSS before.

Analysis
T-test, LOF, and IF-LOF methods used predetermined threshold values of 90%-
97% condence levels. Observaons under 90-97 region were transformed by a
3-segment adapve factor technique, and beyond 97 was considered an outlier.

Conclusion
In the study, we invesgated outlier detecon techniques to enhance the reliability
of GNSS data in dense urban environments.
IF-LOF test performed the worst results due to small data set of epochs
While isolaon forest (IF) performed relavely well, it removed signicantly
more observaons, which resulted in deducon of degrees of freedom
The main dierence between t-test and LOF is caused due to data behavior.
For the local tests, LOF has the most successful results, especially under large
quanle values. However, it removes a small set of reliable GPS satellites
In conclusion, t-test and LOF have the most opmized results, LOF being slightly
more robust. Thus, t-test or LOF methods can be implemented depending on our
condence about the assumpon of data behaviour. Under uncertainty, with this
newly introduced methodology in GNSS context, LOF would be the best opon.
These ndings can signicantly improve GNSS data’s reliability in dense urban en-
vironments. It’s a step forward in enhancements to the posioning algorithm.
